For planning purposes, ATLAS has considered the impact of a worst case accident, defined to be a 35,000 gallon release from a Y-Grade product or HD5 Mix 90,000 gallon tank resulting in the instantaneous formation of a vapor cloud which explodes. A written procedure is in place to limit the storage inventory to 39% of the maximum tank capacity. Using the EPA OCA Guidance Equations a potential radius of impact due to the explosion was calculated to extend to 0.44 miles.  Global positioning system (GPS) locations were gathered on surrounding area residences that could conceivably fall into the worst case catastrophic event, and it was determined that there were none within 0.44 mile radius.   It should be emphasized that the probability of the worst-case catastrophic event evaluated in this report is extremely remote - far less than natural catastrophes such as tornadoes and floods that could produce much more severe and extensive damage and injury.  A consideration of the 0.44-mile radius has been incorporated into our notification and emergency response planning.

ATLAS has implemented safety precautions and procedures designed to prevent and mitigate catastrophic releases.  ATLAS has active operating, maintenance, training, and inspection procedures.  ATLAS provides annual emergency response training to its employees. In addition, ATLAS has coordinated with local emergency responders including the Sayre/Sweetwater Fire Department and the Local Emergency Planning Committee.

ATLAS's management is committed to the following:
- Preventing accidents;
- Training our employees in correct response procedures in the event of an accident;
- Participating in community emergency preparedness;
